"Abstract The growth in PCs, both in business and home use, led to a worldwide shortage of computer memory chips about two years ago, and since then the situation has become worse with the launch of Windows 95 and the damage to a chip factory caused by the Kobe earthquake in Japan. Even though manufacturers are slowly catching up with the demand there is still a thriving black market for chips. They have a very high value and this coupled with their size makes them an attractive target for thieves. The effect of a chip theft on a business is the same as if the PC had been taken, and for most business this is catastrophic. A recent survey carried out in the UK by the DTI indicated that one-third of organizations which were hit by chip theft took more than seven days to get their systems up and running again."
